Using the predefined set of keywords, a content analysis that scrutinizes qualitative and quantitative material (written and visual) was conducted to determine the degree of SDGs representation in ESMs. In particular, the retrieved case study applications were examined to identify explicit themes and concepts related to the keywords, as well as any evidence of outcomes for the SDGs. The assignment of the interlinkages for evaluating the extent to which ESMs address the SDGs-indicators, was allocated based on two approaches: (i) The endogenous perspective defines a direct linkage between a particular SDG and ESM if a SDG-indicator is embedded within the mathematical formulation/framework. However, the linkage can sometimes be direct yet simplified or direct but limited. This is the case when the model does not capture the precise definition of the SDG-indicator as defined by the Global Indicator Framework but instead considers only a simplified definition or captures only certain aspects of the indicator in question (proxy indicators related to the key issues of a specific goal/target). (ii) The exogenous perspective denotes an indirect relationship in which the analysis by the model and subsequent results interpretation derive external insights or offside analysis for policy and practical applications that feed into and support the indicator of a respective SDG. In this context, an indirect correlation does not necessarily imply a model's lack of relevance or thereof lack of capability. Rather, it signifies that the selected applications of the model derive many of the SDGs implications based on external offside analysis. Consequently, a customized scoring system was designed to determine the presence and assess the strength of interlinkages between the SDGs and the shortlisted ESMs (Table 1
                        ). The system assigns a score of 1 (equal weights) to each indicator (
                           x



                              i

                        ) of the SDGs based on its level of relevance to the ESMs judged from the examined case study applications. The accumulated scores earned by each model for each goal (
                           Y



                              ij

                        ) are calculated and then normalized by dividing them with the maximum number of indicators that can be attained per SDG (
                           X



                              ij

                        ) to ensure the scores are comparable across ESMs. The resulting normalized score (
                           NS



                              i

                           j
                        ), ranging from 0 to 1, determines whether an interlinkage exists and labels its strength accordingly (
                           Rank



                              ij

                        ).

Following the selection process for the initial list of 841 modeling tools, a total of ten up-to-date commonly used and broadly applicable ESMs (Table 2
                     ) were shortlisted as the most fitting for the evaluation process in line with the criteria defined in Section 2.1. With respect to the selection process for ESMs case studies as per the criteria defined in Section 2.2, a considerable number of case studies documenting the applications of some ESMs (LEAP, TIMES and GCAM) in diverse contexts were available. For other models (particularly DNE21 and POLES), a relatively smaller number of case studies met the defined criteria, setting the selection threshold across all models for a uniform comparative analysis. As such, twenty case study applications were shortlisted for each model considering the model's core versions and respective variants. For simplicity, only the core version of the models is referred to hereafter. The selection of case studies followed a reverse chronological approach, starting with the most recent studies in 2023 and moving backwards to 2016. For some models (LEAP and TIMES), recent studies, particularly those published in 2022 and 2023, happen to cut across a variety of sustainability related subjects and thus were prioritized over older ones. Conversely, studies selected for other models spanned from 2016 to 2023 to maintain a diverse representation of thematic topics across the case study applications, while still giving preference to newer publications where appropriate. Some models (DNE21 and POLES) appeared mostly in studies that featured more than one model. Nonetheless, the final case studies for these models were selected in a manner that invariably distinguishes their results separately, allowing for a more accurate assessment of the distinct competence of each model. Accordingly, the analysis of the systematic interlinkages mapping was conducted by scrutinizing 200 case study applications employing the ten ESMs (Supplementary Material – Appendix C) across 65 distinct geographical scopes (global, regional, national, and sub-national scales) (Fig. 4
                     ). China and India were the dominant areas of study by ESMs in the context of SD.

The outcomes of examining the extent to which each ESM integrates the 17 SDGs considering the 248 SDGs-indicators (micro-level) are detailed in the Supplementary Material – Appendix D. The degree of variation of the SDGs interlinkages within the shortlisted ESMs is delineated in a heatmap (Fig. 5
                     ), with the models ranked in descending order of their cumulative scores whereby the strength of the interlinkages is defined in a five-level system (None, Weak, Moderate, Substantial, Strong). The results demonstrate the relative sustainability performance of each model based on how well they address the 248 SDGs-indicators. In particular, the analysis reveals that SDG7 (Affordable and Clean Energy) has a “strong” representation in all ESMs except for GCAM, which exhibited “substantial” coverage for this goal. This can be attributed to the model's selected case study applications which mostly examined water, agriculture, land, and climate systems rather than energy systems only. SDG12 (Responsible Consumption and Production) and SDG13 (Climate Action) follow as the next most represented with “moderate” coverage observed across the models. The remaining SDGs (17, 8, 9, 6, 15, 11, 2, 10, 3, 14, 4, and 1 in descending order) show mostly “weak” coverage across all models, while SDG5 (Gender Equality) and SDG16 (Peace, Justice, and Strong Institutions) were not targeted by any model. Fig. 6
                      depicts the cumulative interlinkages between the ESMs and SDGs. Among the highest ranked ESMs, notable instances of applications with a fair consideration of SDGs are exemplified by IMAGE/TIMER (van Sluisveld et al., 2016; van Vuuren et al., 2017), AIM/Enduse (Vishwanathan et al., 2021; Chaichaloempreecha et al., 2022), LEAP (Zhao et al., 2022; Agbossou et al., 2022), GCAM (Turner et al., 2019; Moreno et al., 2023), and MESSAGE (Shen et al., 2022; Zakeri et al., 2022).
